## 2. Tuples

A **tuple** is like a fixed-position array where each position has a known meaning and type. TypeScript has supported tuple types for a long time, and the release notes emphasize that tuples are useful for modeling structured positional data. ([TypeScript][3])

```ts
const coordinates: [number, number] = [39.0, -77.0];
console.log(coordinates);
```

Access works by index:

```ts
console.log(coordinates[0]);
console.log(coordinates[1]);
```

A tuple can represent a compact record:

```ts
const userProfile: [string, number, boolean] = ["Anthony", 32, true];
console.log(userProfile);
```

### Compare to arrays

Array:

```ts
const names: string[] = ["Ava", "Maya", "Jordan"];
```

Tuple:

```ts
const profile: [string, number, boolean] = ["Anthony", 32, true];
```

Arrays usually mean “many values of the same kind.”
Tuples usually mean “a small fixed structure.”

