## 3. Objects

In TypeScript, objects are the fundamental way to group related values, and the handbook’s **Object Types** page says exactly that. ([TypeScript][4])

```ts
const user = {
  name: "Anthony",
  age: 32,
  wantsWebApps: true,
};

console.log(user);
```

Access by property:

```ts
console.log(user.name);
console.log(user.age);
```

Update a property:

```ts
user.age = 33;
console.log(user);
```

Add another property if your type allows it. With a plain inferred object literal, TypeScript expects the original shape to stay consistent, so for beginners it is often easiest to define the full object up front:

```ts
const product = {
  name: "basketball",
  price: 3.23,
  quantity: 25,
};

console.log(product);
```

### Typed object example

```ts
const book: { title: string; author: string; pages: number } = {
  title: "Learning TypeScript",
  author: "Example Author",
  pages: 250,
};

console.log(book.title);
```

